# Your personal vault rules

This file is **not version controlled** and is **not touched by deploys**. Anything you put here is appended after `CLAUDE.base.md` when the takopi container assembles `vault/CLAUDE.md` on start. Your rules win against the base on conflict (they're read later).

`CLAUDE.base.md` defines safety rules and a generic message-handling template, but it deliberately knows nothing about *your* folder layout, language, or tagging style. Everything below is yours to define.

Edit freely. After saving, send `/new` in Telegram (or `docker compose restart takopi` on the VPS) to start a fresh Claude session that picks up the changes.

## Vault structure

Tell the agent what your folders are and what each is for. Pick one of the examples below and edit, or write your own from scratch.

<details>
<summary>Example 1 — PARA with numeric prefixes</summary>

```
/vault
├── 00 Projects/          ← active projects with a defined outcome
├── 10 Areas/
│   └── Inbox/            ← default landing for quick captures
├── 20 Resources/         ← reference material by topic
├── 90 Archive/           ← off-limits, do not access
└── templates/
```

Default Inbox: `10 Areas/Inbox/`. Off-limits: `90 Archive/`.
</details>

<details>
<summary>Example 2 — PARA without prefixes</summary>

```
/vault
├── Projects/
├── Areas/
│   └── Inbox/
├── Resources/
└── Archive/             ← off-limits
```

Default Inbox: `Areas/Inbox/`. Off-limits: `Archive/`.
</details>

<details>
<summary>Example 3 — Flat vault (Zettelkasten-style)</summary>

```
/vault
├── Inbox/
├── notes/
└── reading-list/
```

Default Inbox: `Inbox/`. No off-limits paths beyond the always-blocked `.obsidian/` and `.trash/`.
</details>

